thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Heath","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(on the) heath’ (Middle English <i>he(a)th</i>, Old English <i>hǣth</i>) or else a habitational name from any of numerous places called with this word. The same word also denoted heather, the characteristic plant of heathland areas. This surname has also been established in Dublin, Ireland, since the late 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Haith","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): variant of   Heath  ."]},{"name":"Heathman","meanings":["English: topographic name denoting a dweller ‘on the heath’, from Middle English <i>he(a)th</i> + <i>man(ne)</i>. Compare   Heath   and   Heather  ."]},{"name":"Hatton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hatton (Cheshire, Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Warwickshire), Hatton Hall (Cheshire), or Cold and High Hatton (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Heath  .","English: variant of <b>Atton</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."]},{"name":"Heather","meanings":["English: topographic name denoting a ‘dweller on the heath’, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>hethe</i>; compare   Heath  . The name may also be habitational name from Heather (Leicestershire), from Old English <i>hǣthor</i> ‘heathland’ (<i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + the noun suffix <i>-or</i>) or <i>hǣddre</i> ‘heather’. This surname is widespread in southern England, and also established in Ireland."]},{"name":"Health","meanings":["(1997: 105;2010: NA)","Altered form of English and Scottish   Heath  .","English and Scottish: perhaps a nickname from the vocabulary word <i>health</i>. — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is 105."]},{"name":"Hoad","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived on a heath, from Middle English <i>hoth</i> ‘heath’ (Old English <i>hāth</i>, a byform of Old English <i>hǣth</i>), or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Hoath in Kent. This form was restricted in the Middle Ages to southeastern England, and the surname is still largely confined to Kent, Surrey, and Sussex. Compare   Heath  ."]},{"name":"Heid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Eckhart, Gerd, Gotthilf, Heinz, Klaus, Konrad, Kurt, Manfred, Ralf, Uli.","German, Swiss German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): topographic name from Middle High German <i>heide</i>, German <i>Heide</i> ‘heath, moor, open, uncultivated land’. Compare   Heath  .","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Haido</i>, a short form of any of various compound names beginning with <i>haid</i> ‘heath’ (i.e. wasteland, often with heather)."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John de Heath was born from 1395 to 1455. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. de Heath."},"et":{"From 1395 to 1455–":"1395 kuni 1455–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1432–1495":"1432–1495","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","From 1395 to 1455":"1395 kuni 1455","1 Jun 1432":"1. juuni 1432","1432":"1432","1495":"1495","1395":"1395","Davenham, Cheshire, England":"Davenham, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"From 1395 to 1455–":"vuodesta 1395 vuoteen 1455–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1432–1495":"1432–1495","1395–Male":"1395–Kuollut","From 1395 to 1455":"vuodesta 1395 vuoteen 1455","1 J